COVID-19 and Conflict in the Middle-East¶

- is there an impact?¶

"The fury of the virus illustrates the folly of war." ... "End the sickness of war and fight the disease that is ravaging our world." [1]

So were the words of Antnio Guterres of the United Nations, calling for a worldwide ceasefire on account of the novel COVID-19 virus. Indeed, the virus is of such a scale, that it is challenging societies at practically every level, forcing citizens to distance themselves, for instance. This is certainly a great challenge, and a time to stand together.

In the face a bigger challenge, do people put their differences aside?¶

We'd like to think so, at least the theory. When World War I was brought to a halt by an armistice, a terrible influenza had reigned on its soldiers, and it's been speculated to have played a part in the outcome of the war. Indeed, more American soldiers were killed by the flu than in battle during the war [2].

With the world's healthcare systems being pushed to its limits, it's no wonder authorities are worried.

So where's these conflicts?¶

Conflict in the Middle-East has been prevelant for decades. The area has been affected by wars, and this may have inhibited the development of their infrastructure. This would leave the countries vulnerable to the virus as well. Here we're going to inspect these countries.

The countries in question are: Bahrain, Cyprus, Egypt, Iran, Iraq, Israel, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Turkey, United Arab Emirates and Yemen.

The conflicts looked at are categorised by Explosions/Remote violence, Protests, Battles, Strategic Developments, Violence against Civilians and Riots.

COVID-19 data sourced from [3], but originally provided by John's Hopkins University Center. As for the conflict dataset, it was sourced from The Armed Conflict Location and Event Data Project (ACLED) [4].

Why this matters¶

There's little telling what impact the virus is going to have. The United Nations have expressed their concerns on future impact on domestic violance cases, as indicators indeed show that there's a current increase [5].

Let's look at all conflicts in the Middle-Eastern region in the form of a heat map. We'll start by comparing last year to this year and see if there's any noticible difference.¶

That's curious, the conflict seems to maintain fairly prevelant, currently as it did last year. Is it possible that the virus is not affecting the region's conflict at all?¶

If we examine the entirety of 2020's conflict data, however, can we see any effect?¶

As can be seen, even though the conflicts are consistently numerous, there seems to be a trend of lower frequency accross conflicts. Do compare with the COVID-19 plot above. Pay special attention to April.¶

Now let's visualize this on a weekly-basis, to hopefully get a better feeling for the trend.¶

That's interesting. Conflict events seemed to have spiked in week 8, but dropped rapidly after that. We're also observing an increase again after week 15.¶

So what are these events? Fatalities seem to follow suit with the events, meaning they're probably more serious.¶

Above you can explore the weekly frequency of the different conflict events that have occured in 2020 in the Middle-East. Note the large drop in Explosions and Protests around week 10.¶

While the nature of the relationship between COVID-19 and conflicts within the Middle-East have not entirely been revealed, this visual exploration shows that there is at least something to the case that the virus could be having an effect.¶

We hope you enjoyed this exploration, and continue to explore the widespread impact that the virus is having all over the world.¶
